        "behavior": "; 74163 (SN74F163A) — synchronous presettable 4-bit binary counter with\n; synchronous clear. Derived from the description (datasheet p.1), the\n; logic diagram (p.3), and the state diagram (p.2); this datasheet has no\n; numbered function table. Priority at each rising clock edge:\n; clear (pin /CLR LOW) > load (pin /LOAD LOW) > count (ENP and ENT both\n; HIGH) > hold.\n;\n; SEQUENTIAL-PART CLOCK CONVENTION (74574.yaml): GALasm's .R registered\n; outputs are clocked by the GAL22V10's dedicated pin-1 clock\n; (galasmManual.txt section 3.4). That pin-1 clock role is played by the\n; part's named clock pin — here CLK, rising-edge triggered. CLK therefore\n; does NOT appear as a term in any equation below; the .R suffix implies it.\n;\n; Equations are physical-level GALasm: '/' is the complement operator and\n; signal names are this file's pin names with any active-low '/' prefix\n; dropped (pin /CLR is GAL signal CLR, so '/CLR' below means \"pin /CLR is\n; LOW\"). Each Qn has four kinds of product term, every one carrying CLR\n; (pin /CLR HIGH, i.e. not clearing):\n;   load:  /LOAD * <data>                     — synchronous preset\n;   count: LOAD * ENP * ENT * <toggle/carry>  — binary up-count\n;   hold:  LOAD * /ENP * Qn  and  LOAD * /ENT * Qn — count disabled\n; The synchronous clear needs no terms of its own: with pin /CLR LOW no\n; term is true, so every register loads 0 at the next rising edge,\n; regardless of /LOAD, ENP, and ENT (p.1: clear overrides load and count).\n;\n; QA (LSB) toggles whenever counting; each higher bit toggles when all\n; lower bits are 1 (the look-ahead carry), otherwise holds while counting.\nQA.R =   CLR * /LOAD * A\n       + CLR *  LOAD * ENP * ENT * /QA\n       + CLR *  LOAD * /ENP * QA\n       + CLR *  LOAD * /ENT * QA\n\nQB.R =   CLR * /LOAD * B\n       + CLR *  LOAD * ENP * ENT *  QA * /QB\n       + CLR *  LOAD * ENP * ENT * /QA *  QB\n       + CLR *  LOAD * /ENP * QB\n       + CLR *  LOAD * /ENT * QB\n\nQC.R =   CLR * /LOAD * C\n       + CLR *  LOAD * ENP * ENT *  QA *  QB * /QC\n       + CLR *  LOAD * ENP * ENT * /QA *  QC\n       + CLR *  LOAD * ENP * ENT * /QB *  QC\n       + CLR *  LOAD * /ENP * QC\n       + CLR *  LOAD * /ENT * QC\n\nQD.R =   CLR * /LOAD * D\n       + CLR *  LOAD * ENP * ENT *  QA *  QB *  QC * /QD\n       + CLR *  LOAD * ENP * ENT * /QA *  QD\n       + CLR *  LOAD * ENP * ENT * /QB *  QD\n       + CLR *  LOAD * ENP * ENT * /QC *  QD\n       + CLR *  LOAD * /ENP * QD\n       + CLR *  LOAD * /ENT * QD\n\n; Ripple-carry output (combinational): HIGH while the count is 15 and ENT\n; is HIGH — ENT is fed forward to enable RCO; ENP does not affect RCO\n; (p.1). Counting spikes can occur on RCO (p.1); this unit-delay model\n; does not reproduce them.\nRCO = ENT * QA * QB * QC * QD\n",
        "clock": "CLK"
      },
      "overrides": {}
    },
